arding war and military life, and how such constructions may also intensify militarism. By examining news and documentary media produced since September 11, 2001, Vavrus demonstrates that news narratives that include women use feminism selectively in gender equality narratives, which tend to reinforce historically resonant gender, race, and class identity constructions. She ultimately asserts that such reporting advances post-feminism, which, in tandem with banal militarism, subtly pushes military solutions for an array of problems women and girls face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFeminism and mass mediazUnited States. 0aMass media and warzUnited States. 0aMilitarismzUnited States. 0aWomen and the militaryzUnited States. 0aWomen soldiers in mass media. 0aWomen soldierszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afeminist, women, war, post-feminist, media, military, 911, political, Department of Defense, U.S., militarism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813576848zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813576848423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813576848.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK